Lebanon's full-blown crisis
BEIRUT — — Looking back, financial crises usually seem to have precursors; but they rarely clearly point to how history will unfold.
This is the case for Lebanon now, where a foreseeable crisis has thrown the country into high levels of instability.
Since the end of Lebanon’s long civil war (1975-1990), its economic and political systems have been supported by external borrowing, which inevitably led to a sustained rise in public debt.
At some point, inflows of external capital had to stop. That point came at the end of 2019, when a series of negative shocks hit.
This "sudden stop" of capital flows brought about a severe triple crisis for the country.
The first issue is the balance of payments.
Lebanon’s current-account deficit reaches 25% of GDP, with exports too small even to cover necessary import costs.
The second issue is fiscal.
Public debt in Lebanon now totals over 150% of GDP.
Government revenues are collapsing under the weight of an economic recession, with budget deficits already large, accounting for 10% of GDP in 2019 and expanding rapidly.
Most importantly, Lebanon is also experiencing a banking crisis.
Major banks, which have been the main recipients of foreign capital inflows, have made substantial investments in Lebanese sovereign debt (on average accounting for 50% of their portfolios) and are now essentially insolvent.
These crises together are pushing the Lebanese economy into a abyss.
Companies eager for loans and imports have begun laying off workers or shutting down entirely.
An economic downturn could lead to another Lebanese Great Depression.
The main capital source supporting Lebanon's fragile political and economic system is not oil but expatriates, who invest due to high interest rates and the fixed exchange rate tied to the dollar.
It is no wonder then that there are signs of "Dutch disease": deposits have grown to over 400% of GDP, creating a wealth effect that has reduced the national savings rate to an unlikely level—3% of GDP.
Inequality is high and rising.
From 2000 to 2015, the real (inflation-adjusted) exchange rate appreciated by about 50%, significantly weakening tradable sectors.
Due to the lack of exportable goods and services, Lebanon has been losing educated youth.
More importantly, large capital inflows have allowed sectarian elites to consolidate their positions through patronage rather than performance.
These elites siphoned off wealth from both public and private sectors, establishing a bloated clientelistic ruling group.
While this ensured political stability in what was otherwise a chaotic region, it failed to meet basic needs.
Even electricity supply is intermittent and unreliable, while broader macroeconomic challenges remain unresolved.
The financial crisis sparked a political uprising.
A popular revolutionary movement took to the streets, opposing sectarianism and demanding an end to corruption.
Nevertheless, so far, the country’s establishment has responded overwhelmingly to the economic problems facing Lebanon in a way that benefits the elites, suggesting that this crisis may ultimately be “resolved” with the support of the poor and middle class, thereby further entrenching sectarian politics.
For example, the state refused to introduce capital controls, allowing the main shareholders of each bank—among them ruling politicians—to decide how much cash could be withdrawn quantitatively.
In practice, this allows elites to transfer their capital abroad while ordinary citizens struggle to access their deposits.
Moreover, the central bank lowered deposit rates but has not yet reduced public debt rates, thereby boosting bank profits.
Despite declining international reserves, Lebanon continues to repay its major external debts owed to domestic banks.
There are signs that it may start selling off state assets at fire-sale prices to elite-associated entities.
Meanwhile, the official exchange rate remains unchanged, while elites allow access to cheap US dollars, leaving ordinary citizens facing a rapid decline in the black market rate, which is currently at a 40% discount.
As the country begins printing liras to pay civil servants’ wages, devaluation will accelerate.
Factually, the central bank is already using liras to pay interest on dollar deposits (which make up over 80% of all deposits), thus creating conditions for inflationary debt relief.
By shifting the cost of debt reduction to depositors through "liraization," bank equity can largely be spared.
If this scenario comes true, Lebanon's middle class will significantly shrink due to reduced real wages and pension values, and the liquidation of savings.
The migration of educated young people will accelerate, and even the economic interests of migrant communities – upon which this system relies – will be harmed.
If the sectarian system is to survive under these conditions, it will rule over a poor population that can be controlled by increasingly affordable shelters.
Ultimately, Lebanon will find itself in a similar situation to Venezuela.
In contrast, the new republic that revolutionaries aim to establish will take a completely different approach.
Revolutionaries want to improve Lebanon, not abandon it.
They believe that it performs far below its potential, and that performance, elite management, and social justice should replace corruption, cronyism, and inequality.
They hope to build vibrant high-tech industries, make agriculture more environmentally sustainable, position the country as a cultural powerhouse, and create greater synergies with immigrant communities.
To achieve these goals, the reform movement hopes to seek an orderly reduction of public debt, which will be guaranteed by bank equity, and enforce a reduction of deposits exceeding 1% of total deposits by more than 50%.
They support moderate currency devaluation and a complete improvement of the business environment to enhance export competitiveness.
They will pursue deep fiscal restructuring, emphasizing the elimination of corruption and increasing spending on social programs and infrastructure.
With support from the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the inevitable recession will be mitigated.
The current dispute over the composition of Lebanon's next cabinet is part of the larger struggle as the country seeks new political solutions.
The financial crisis poses a fatal threat to the country; but it also represents an opportunity for political change.
The future of Lebanon remains uncertain.
